price vs.Â volume

# Create a scatterplot of price vs. volume (x * y * z).
# This is a very rough approximation for a diamond's volume.

# Create a new variable for volume in the diamonds data frame.
# This will be useful in a later exercise.

# Don't make any adjustments to the plot just yet.

# This assignment is not graded and
# will be marked as correct when you submit.

# ENTER YOUR CODE BELOW THIS LINE
# =================================================================
data(diamonds)
library(ggplot2)
diamonds$volume <- diamonds$x * diamonds$y * diamonds$z
ggplot(aes(x=volume, y=price), data=diamonds) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.01) + 
  xlim(0,quantile(diamonds$volume, 0.99)) + 
  ylim(0,quantile(diamonds$price, 0.99))
## Warning: Removed 943 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Findings: price vs.Â volume

Observations?:

  • most values fall in the range of a lower volume
  • increased variability in price with higher volume
  • generally increased price with increased volume
  • some clustering of volumes occurs
  • outliers: some volumes are 0!

Mean Price by Clarity

# Use the function dplyr package
# to create a new data frame containing
# info on diamonds by clarity.

# Name the data frame diamondsByClarity

# The data frame should contain the following
# variables in this order.

#       (1) mean_price
#       (2) median_price
#       (3) min_price
#       (4) max_price
#       (5) n

# where n is the number of diamonds in each
# level of clarity.

# This assignment WILL BE automatically
# graded!

# DO NOT ALTER THE NEXT THREE LINES OF CODE.
# ======================================================
suppressMessages(library(ggplot2))
suppressMessages(library(dplyr))
## Warning: package 'dplyr' was built under R version 3.2.2
data(diamonds)

# ENTER YOUR CODE BELOW THIS LINE
# ======================================================
data(diamonds)
diamondsByClarity <- diamonds %>%
  dplyr::group_by(clarity) %>% 
  dplyr::summarise(mean_price = mean(price),
        median_price = median(price),
        min_price = min(price), 
        max_price = max(price),
        n = n())

Bar Charts of Mean Price

# Weâve created summary data frames with the mean price
# by clarity and color. You can run the code in R to
# verify what data is in the variables diamonds_mp_by_clarity
# and diamonds_mp_by_color.

# Your task is to write additional code to create two bar plots
# on one output image using the grid.arrange() function from the package
# gridExtra.

# This assignment is not graded and
# will be marked as correct when you submit.

# See the Instructor Notes for more info on bar charts
# and for a hint on this task.

# DO NOT DELETE THE LINES OF CODE BELOW
# ===================================================================
data(diamonds)
suppressMessages(library(gridExtra))
## Warning: package 'gridExtra' was built under R version 3.2.2
suppressMessages(library(ggplot2))
suppressMessages(library(dplyr))

diamonds_by_clarity <- group_by(diamonds, clarity)
diamonds_mp_by_clarity <- summarise(diamonds_by_clarity, mean_price = mean(price))

diamonds_by_color <- group_by(diamonds, color)
diamonds_mp_by_color <- summarise(diamonds_by_color, mean_price = mean(price))

# ENTER YOUR CODE BELOW THIS LINE
# ===================================================================
p1 <- ggplot(data=diamonds_mp_by_clarity, aes(x=clarity, y=mean_price)) + geom_bar(stat="identity")
p2 <- ggplot(data=diamonds_mp_by_color, aes(x=color, y=mean_price)) + geom_bar(stat="identity")
grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol=2)

Trends in Mean Price

Observations in each of the bar charts for mean price by clarity and mean price by color?

  • increase in price for colours E->J
  • sharp maximum at clarity SI2 and sharp minimum at VVS1 - strange :( - I would assume that price increases as clarity increases

suppressMessages(library(dplyr))
suppressMessages(library(tidyr))
## Warning: package 'tidyr' was built under R version 3.2.2
setwd('h:/Dokumente/GitHub/2015_Data_Analyst_Project_4/lesson3/')
mentalhealth <- read.csv('Suicide male indicator file UL 20100916.csv', header=T, check.names=F)
mentalhealth <- mentalhealth %>%
  tidyr::gather("year", "fraction", 2:length(mentalhealth)) %>%
  dplyr::filter(!is.na(fraction))
mentalhealth$year = as.numeric(levels(mentalhealth$year))[mentalhealth$year]
colnames(mentalhealth)[1] <- "country"
mentalhealth.now <- mentalhealth %>%
  dplyr::group_by(country) %>% 
  dplyr::summarise(nowyear=max(year)) %>%
  dplyr::left_join(mentalhealth, c("nowyear" = "year", "country" = "country")) %>%
  dplyr::rename(nowfraction=fraction)
